sec.p:
We quantified serial dependence effects (SDE) to examine how prior visual experiences influence current perceptual reports (Figure 1B), and whether these dependencies affect learning specificity across experimental conditions. To estimate SDE, we fit a linear mixed-effects (LME) model (Figure 1C) that evaluated the influence of prior target stimuli (up to’ 10 trials back) on current reports. For each lag n, the model estimates a coefficient Wn; we refer to this coefficient simply as W-bias. These coefficients represent the magnitude of the serial-dependence effect for each n-back stimulus. We modeled the report probability as
P(T0∣T0)=P0+∑n=110Wn⋅sTn \begin{document}$$\displaystyle P\left(T_{0} \mid T_{0}\right)=P_{0}+\sum_{n=1}^{10} W_{n} \cdot s T_{n}$$\end{document}
Where:

On each trial, the visual system generates an internal sensory response xt, added with stimulus-independent sensory noise σ. Using the two templates and the current category prior, a posterior responsibility can be computed
rt=P(B∣xt) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle r_{t}=P\left(B \mid x_{t}\right)$$\end{document}
i.e., how strongly the current sample supports category B rather than A. This responsibility is used for:

Serial dependence follows directly. An easy trial shifts the internal boundary; subsequent hard trials are ambiguous and therefore sensitive to the exact positioning of the boundary. Because hard trials do not strongly update the templates, the boundary persists and the bias extends across multiple lags. In the simulations this link is verified by computing the boundary shift
Δmt=mtpost −mtpre : \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \Delta m_{t}=m_{t}^{\text {post }}-m_{t}^{\text {pre }}:$$\end{document}
and showing that Δmt, differs after EASY-A versus EASY-B trials. Moreover, for EASY→HARD pairs, Δmt−1 predicts the probability of reporting B on the next hard trial.

Likelihoods use fixed internal σ:
LA(t)∝exp⁡[−12(xt−μA,tpreσ)2],LB(t)∝exp⁡[−12(xt−μB,tpreσ)2] \begin{document}$$\displaystyle L_{A}(t) \propto \exp \left[-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x_{t}-\mu_{A, t}^{p r e}}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right], \quad L_{B}(t) \propto \exp \left[-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x_{t}-\mu_{B, t}^{p r e}}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right]$$\end{document}
Posterior responsibility:
rt=pB,tLB(t)(1−pB,t)LA(t)+pB,tLB(t) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle r_{t}=\frac{p_{B, t} L_{B}(t)}{\left(1-p_{B, t}\right) L_{A}(t)+p_{B, t} L_{B}(t)}$$\end{document}
Decision: report B if rt > 0.5.

To reduce learning from ambiguous stimuli, we optionally apply a confidence gate based on posterior distance from indifference:


rt−0.5∣
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle r_{t}-0.5 \mid$$\end{document}



A bounded confidence gate is:


ct=min{1,max(cmin(2|rt−0.5|)k)}
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle c_{t}=\min \left\{1, \max \left(c_{\min }\left(2\left|r_{t}-0.5\right|\right)^{k}\right)\right\}$$\end{document}



This downweights learning from ambiguous (dummy) trials (rt ≈ 0.5).

Prediction:


x^t=(1−rt)μA,tpre+rtμB,tpre
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \hat{x}_{t}=\left(1-r_{t}\right) \mu_{A, t}^{p r e}+r_{t} \mu_{B, t}^{p r e}$$\end{document}



Volatility update (vt increases when new observation is far from the predicted, x^t\begin{document}$\widehat{x}_{t}$\end{document}):


vt=(1−λ)vt−1+λ(xt−x^t)2
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle v_{t}=(1-\lambda) v_{t-1}+\lambda\left(x_{t}-\hat{x}_{t}\right)^{2}$$\end{document}



Process noise:


Qt=clip(Q0+gVvt,0,Qmax )
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle Q_{t}=\operatorname{clip}\left(Q_{0}+g_{V} v_{t}, 0, Q_{\text {max }}\right)$$\end{document}

Prediction uncertainty (updated by process noise):


Pk,tpre =Pk,t−1post +Qt
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle P_{k, t}^{\text {pre }}=P_{k, t-1}^{\text {post }}+Q_{t}$$\end{document}



Observation uncertainty (fixed):


R=Rbase σ2
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle R=R_{\text {base }} \sigma^{2}$$\end{document}



Responsibility-weighted effective noise:


RA,t=R1−rt,RB,t=Rrt
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle R_{A, t}=\frac{R}{1-r_{t}}, \quad R_{B, t}=\frac{R}{r_{t}}$$\end{document}



Kalman gains:


KA,t=PA,tpre PA,tpre +RA,t,KB,t=PB,tpre PB,tpre +RB,t
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle K_{A, t}=\frac{P_{A, t}^{\text {pre }}}{P_{A, t}^{\text {pre }}+R_{A, t}}, \quad K_{B, t}=\frac{P_{B, t}^{\text {pre }}}{P_{B, t}^{\text {pre }}+R_{B, t}}$$\end{document}



Updates:


μA,tpost =μA,tpre +ctKA,t(xt−μA,tpre )μB,tpost =μB,tpre +ctKB,t(xt−μB,tpre )
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} & \mu_{A, t}^{\text {post }}=\mu_{A, t}^{\text {pre }}+c_{t} K_{A, t}\left(x_{t}-\mu_{A, t}^{\text {pre }}\right) \\ & \mu_{B, t}^{\text {post }}=\mu_{B, t}^{\text {pre }}+c_{t} K_{B, t}\left(x_{t}-\mu_{B, t}^{\text {pre }}\right)\end{aligned}$$\end{document}



Boundary step:


Δmt=mtpost −mtpre 
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \Delta m_{t}=m_{t}^{\text {post }}-m_{t}^{\text {pre }}$$\end{document}



Large mismatch → larger vt→ larger Qt→ faster re-learning.

History integration:


pB,traw =(1−η)pB,t−1+ηrt
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle p_{B, t}^{\text {raw }}=(1-\eta) p_{B, t-1}+\eta r_{t}$$\end{document}



Relaxation toward neutrality:


pB,t=wpB,traw +(1−w)⋅0.5
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle p_{B, t}=w p_{B, t}^{\text {raw }}+(1-w) \cdot 0.5$$\end{document}



Where


w=e−1/τ
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle w=e^{-1 / \tau}$$\end{document}



So:

oddst=pB,t1−pB,t
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle _{t}=\frac{p_{B, t}}{1-p_{B, t}}$$\end{document}



Even if templates were frozen, this would generate serial dependence. When both mechanisms are active, SDE reflects both persistent boundary shifts and prior drift.
